<div id="review_2089553943" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2089553943" />
    <a title="Suha" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2810879-suha"><img alt="Suha" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1433671918p2/2810879.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2089553943?book_show_action=true">Oct 25, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Suha" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Suha" href="/user/show/2810879-suha">Suha</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140117677" href="/book/show/94737.Ice_Candy_Man">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2089553943" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1946808411054274426">*contains spoilers*<br/>I was truly excited to read a book about the partition. However, this book was a colossal disappointment. Not only is the writing very vague and ambiguous (leaving you with a lot of &apos;???&apos;), but I also don&apos;t see how this is written from a child&apos;s perspective. The kind of observations Lenny makes, the very writing and use of difficult words, the actions this &apos;innocent&apos; child does.<br/>I mean, everyone has sex on their mind in this book, even the kids, more or less. Is India&apos;s overpop</span>
  <span id="freeText1946808411054274426" style="display:none">*contains spoilers*<br />I was truly excited to read a book about the partition. However, this book was a colossal disappointment. Not only is the writing very vague and ambiguous (leaving you with a lot of '???'), but I also don't see how this is written from a child's perspective. The kind of observations Lenny makes, the very writing and use of difficult words, the actions this 'innocent' child does.<br />I mean, everyone has sex on their mind in this book, even the kids, more or less. Is India's overpopulation being justified here or what? Most of those particular passages contributed nothing to the story overall.<br /><br />It might be wrong of me to compare but to put this book side by side with Persepolis (which comprises of a similar theme), I found the protagonist to be charmless, for the lack of a better word. It felt as though picking a child for a protagonist was a move to say anything and get away with it using her 'ignorance and innocence' as a scapegoat by the writer.<br /><br />The book dribbles on to irrelevant details and unnecessary situations. There is a mention of Ayah's 'voluminous globules' and the like every 5th page. We get it, she's attractive. The fact now haunts me at night, thanks a lot. The characters are unrelatable brick walls. The actual details of the partition are lost between this bland narration. However I will say that the horrors of what went on during that time were gripping whenever it was described. I also found Lenny's encounter with Gandhi particularly interesting. Iqbal's poetry interspersed within the writing was also nice.<br /><br />But all-in-all, I will hurriedly pass this book on to the next poor junior who will have to read this for a series of tasteless Literature classes in their final year. Sayonara.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1946808411054274426" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


